                  </persName>
            . On the 21st of July, I was at work with the prisoner for Mr. Botheroyd, who lives in <placeName id="t18240916-197-crimeloc1069">Golden-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18240916-197-crimeloc1069" type="placeName" value="Golden-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18240916-197-crimeloc1069" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240916-197-off1067 t18240916-197-crimeloc1069"></join>. This hydrometer was missed: I followed him to Harbord's shop; he saw me, and ran out; I collared him, and Harbord gave me the hydrometer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240916-197-person1653">
                  RICHARD 
                  HARBORD
               <interp inst="t18240916-197-person1653" type="surname" value="HARBORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-197-person1653" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-197-person1653" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Beech-street, Barbican. On 21st July, the prisoner came into my shop between eight and nine at night, and asked me to let him leave a small parcel, and before I gave an answer, he left the shop. He returned for it in a quarter of an hour, and seemed in great confusion; Passingham followed close at his heels, and said,</p>
               <p>"What are you going there for?" He said,</p>
               <p>"Nothing, sir." I gave the parcel to Passingham; it was an hydrometer.</p>

               <p>
            
